# AutoReach — Project Context for Cursor AI

## What this project is

AutoReach is an AI-powered food rescue platform built for the GenAI Genesis Hackathon in Toronto. The project is inspired by Food for the Capital (foodforthecapital.ca), an Ottawa-based food bank organization.

The core problem we are solving is this: food banks like Food for the Capital spend enormous amounts of time manually calling grocery store managers to arrange surplus food pickups. Most calls go unanswered. Emails get ignored. By the time a store agrees to donate, the food has sometimes already been thrown out. This coordination overhead burns out volunteers and coordinators, and it means less food reaches the families who need it.

Our solution is a voice AI agent that automatically calls grocery store managers, has a real, intelligent conversation with them, handles objections naturally, and books a recurring surplus pickup — all without a human coordinator making a single call. The system also predicts which Ottawa neighbourhoods will see increased food insecurity demand, gives volunteers optimized pickup routes, and generates personalized impact reports for donors.

The hackathon category we are targeting is "Best AI for Community Impact," sponsored by Google, which asks for the most innovative AI solution addressing environmental or sustainability challenges with meaningful real-world impact.

---

## The three-layer AI architecture

Understanding how the AI works is essential for writing good code in this project. There are three distinct layers that work together in a loop during every phone call.

**Vapi** is the telephony and audio layer. It physically dials phone numbers, streams audio in and out of the call in real time, transcribes what the store manager says into text using speech-to-text, and converts our agent's text responses back into speech using a voice model (ElevenLabs). Vapi does not contain any intelligence — it is purely infrastructure. Every time the manager finishes speaking, Vapi sends an HTTP POST request (a webhook) to our FastAPI backend containing the full conversation transcript so far. Our backend then replies with the next thing the agent should say, and Vapi speaks it. This loop repeats for every turn of the conversation.

**LangChain** is the reasoning layer. It lives inside our FastAPI backend and receives the conversation transcript from the Vapi webhook. LangChain is a framework for building AI agents that can reason in steps and decide which tools to use. In our case, the agent decides whether it already knows enough to respond or whether it needs to search the knowledge base first. LangChain orchestrates the full reasoning cycle: receive message, optionally search RAG, construct a prompt with conversation history and retrieved context, call the language model (GPT-4), and return the response.

**RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation)** is the memory layer. It is a collection of documents we write ourselves — about Food for the Capital, how pickups work, answers to common objections, the tone and language the agent should use — stored in a vector database. These documents are chunked into small pieces, converted into numerical vector representations (embeddings) using OpenAI's embedding model, and stored in pgvector (which runs inside our existing PostgreSQL database). When LangChain needs to answer a specific question, it converts the manager's message into a vector too and finds the most semantically similar document chunks — meaning it finds relevant content by meaning, not just keyword matching. This retrieved context is then injected into the prompt so GPT-4 can give accurate, specific answers grounded in real information about our organization.

The complete call loop works like this: manager speaks → Vapi transcribes → FastAPI webhook receives transcript → LangChain searches RAG if needed → GPT-4 generates response → FastAPI returns response to Vapi → Vapi speaks it → repeat.

---

## Tech stack

The frontend is **Next.js 16** with **Tailwind CSS v4** and **TypeScript**. It lives in the `frontend/` folder.

The backend is **FastAPI** (Python 3.14) with **uvicorn** as the server. It lives in the `backend/` folder. Package management uses **uv** (not pip) — to install packages use `uv add package-name`, and to run the server use `uv run uvicorn main:app --reload`.

The database is **PostgreSQL 15** running in Docker, accessed via **SQLAlchemy** with **psycopg2-binary** as the driver. We also use **pgvector** as a PostgreSQL extension for storing and querying embeddings, which means we do not need a separate vector database like Pinecone.

The AI stack uses **LangChain** for agent orchestration, **OpenAI** for both the language model (GPT-4) and embeddings, and **Vapi** for the voice calling infrastructure.

Everything runs locally via **Docker Compose**. The `docker-compose.yml` at the project root defines three services: `db` (PostgreSQL), `backend` (FastAPI), and `frontend` (Next.js). The database host inside Docker is `db`, not `localhost`, because Docker's internal network routes by service name.

